SyslogTimeStamp.name: SyslogTimeStamp
SyslogTimeStamp.description: A date-time specification. This type is similar to the DateAndTime type defined in the SNMPv2-TC, except the subsecond granulation is microseconds instead of deciseconds and a zero-length string can be used to indicate a missing value. field octets contents range ----- ------ -------- ----- 1 1-2 year* 0..65536 2 3 month 1..12 3 4 day 1..31 4 5 hour 0..23 5 6 minutes 0..59 6 7 seconds 0..60 (use 60 for leap-second) 7 8-10 microseconds* 0..999999 8 11 direction from UTC '+' / '-' 9 12 hours from UTC* 0..13 10 13 minutes from UTC 0..59 * Notes: - the value of year is in network-byte order - the value of microseconds is in network-byte order - daylight saving time in New Zealand is +13 For example, Tuesday May 26, 1992 at 1:30:15 PM EDT would be displayed as: 1992-5-26,13:30:15.0,-4:0 Note that if only local time is known, then timezone information (fields 11-13) is not present.

SyslogParamValueString.name: SyslogParamValueString
SyslogParamValueString.description: The value of a SYSLOG SD-PARAM is represented using the ISO/IEC IS 10646-1 character set, encoded as an octet string using the UTF-8 transformation format described in RFC 3629. Since additional code points are added by amendments to the 10646 standard from time to time, implementations must be prepared to encounter any code point from 0x00000000 to 0x7fffffff. Byte sequences that do not correspond to the valid UTF-8 encoding of a code point or that are outside this range are prohibited. Similarly, overlong UTF-8 sequences are prohibited. UTF-8 may require multiple bytes to represent a single character / code point; thus, the length of this object in octets may be different from the number of characters encoded. Similarly, size constraints refer to the number of encoded octets, not the number of characters represented by an encoding.
SyslogParamValueString.reference: RFC 3629: UTF-8, a transformation format of ISO 10646

syslogMsgTableMaxSize.name: syslogMsgTableMaxSize
syslogMsgTableMaxSize.description: The maximum number of SYSLOG messages that may be held in syslogMsgTable. A particular setting does not guarantee that there is sufficient memory available for the maximum number of table entries indicated by this object. A value of 0 means no fixed limit. If an application reduces the limit while there are SYSLOG messages in the syslogMsgTable, the SYSLOG messages that are in the syslogMsgTable for the longest time MUST be discarded to bring the table down to the new limit. The value of this object should be kept in nonvolatile memory.

syslogMsgEnableNotifications.name: syslogMsgEnableNotifications
syslogMsgEnableNotifications.description: Indicates whether syslogMsgNotification notifications are generated. The value of this object should be kept in nonvolatile memory.

syslogMsgTable.name: syslogMsgTable
syslogMsgTable.description: A table containing recent SYSLOG messages. The size of the table is controlled by the syslogMsgTableMaxSize object.

syslogMsgIndex.name: syslogMsgIndex
syslogMsgIndex.description: A monotonically increasing number used to identify entries in the syslogMsgTable. When syslogMsgIndex reaches the maximum value (4294967295), the value wraps back to 1. Applications periodically polling the syslogMsgTable for new entries should take into account that a complete rollover of syslogMsgIndex will happen if more than 4294967294 messages are received during a poll interval.

syslogMsgFacility.name: syslogMsgFacility
syslogMsgFacility.reference: RFC 5424: The Syslog Protocol (Section 6.2.1) RFC 5427: Textual Conventions for Syslog Management
syslogMsgFacility.description: The facility of the SYSLOG message.

syslogMsgSeverity.name: syslogMsgSeverity
syslogMsgSeverity.reference: RFC 5424: The Syslog Protocol (Section 6.2.1) RFC 5427: Textual Conventions for Syslog Management
syslogMsgSeverity.description: The severity of the SYSLOG message

syslogMsgVersion.name: syslogMsgVersion
syslogMsgVersion.description: The version of the SYSLOG message. A value of 0 indicates that the version is unknown.

syslogMsgTimeStamp.name: syslogMsgTimeStamp
syslogMsgTimeStamp.description: The timestamp of the SYSLOG message. A zero-length string is returned if the timestamp is unknown.

syslogMsgHostName.name: syslogMsgHostName
syslogMsgHostName.description: The hostname and the (optional) domain name of the SYSLOG message. A zero-length string indicates an unknown hostname. The SYSLOG protocol specification constrains this string to printable US-ASCII code points.

syslogMsgAppName.name: syslogMsgAppName
syslogMsgAppName.description: The app-name of the SYSLOG message. A zero-length string indicates an unknown app-name. The SYSLOG protocol specification constrains this string to printable US-ASCII code points.

syslogMsgProcID.name: syslogMsgProcID
syslogMsgProcID.description: The procid of the SYSLOG message. A zero-length string indicates an unknown procid. The SYSLOG protocol specification constrains this string to printable US-ASCII code points.

syslogMsgMsgID.name: syslogMsgMsgID
syslogMsgMsgID.description: The msgid of the SYSLOG message. A zero-length string indicates an unknown msgid. The SYSLOG protocol specification constrains this string to printable US-ASCII code points.

syslogMsgSDParams.name: syslogMsgSDParams
syslogMsgSDParams.description: The total number of structured data element parameters carried in the SYSLOG message. This number effectively indicates the number of entries in the syslogMsgSDTable. It can be used, for example, by a notification receiver to determine whether a notification carried all structured data element parameters of a SYSLOG message.

syslogMsgMsg.name: syslogMsgMsg
syslogMsgMsg.description: The message part of the SYSLOG message. The syntax does not impose a size restriction. Implementations of this MIB module may truncate the message part of the SYSLOG message such that it fits into the size constraints imposed by the implementation environment. Such truncations can also happen elsewhere in the SYSLOG forwarding chain. If the first octets contain the value 'EFBBBF'h, then the rest of the message is a UTF-8 string. Since SYSLOG messages may be truncated at arbitrary octet boundaries during forwarding, the message may contain invalid UTF-8 encodings at the end.

syslogMsgSDTable.name: syslogMsgSDTable
syslogMsgSDTable.description: A table containing structured data elements of SYSLOG messages.

syslogMsgSDParamIndex.name: syslogMsgSDParamIndex
syslogMsgSDParamIndex.description: This object indexes the structured data element parameters contained in a SYSLOG message. The first structured data element parameter has the index value 1, and subsequent parameters are indexed by incrementing the index of the previous parameter. The index increases across structured data element boundaries so that the value reflects the position of a structured data element parameter in a SYSLOG message.

syslogMsgSDID.name: syslogMsgSDID
syslogMsgSDID.description: The name (SD-ID) of a structured data element. The SYSLOG protocol specification constrains this string to printable US-ASCII code points.

syslogMsgSDParamName.name: syslogMsgSDParamName
syslogMsgSDParamName.description: The name of a parameter of the structured data element. The SYSLOG protocol specification constrains this string to printable US-ASCII code points.

syslogMsgSDParamValue.name: syslogMsgSDParamValue
syslogMsgSDParamValue.description: The value of the parameter of a SYSLOG message identified by the index of this table. The value is stored in the unescaped format.

syslogMsgNotification.name: syslogMsgNotification
syslogMsgNotification.description: The syslogMsgNotification is generated when a new SYSLOG message is received and the value of syslogMsgGenerateNotifications is true. Implementations may add syslogMsgSDParamValue objects as long as the resulting notification fits into the size constraints imposed by the implementation environment and the notification message size constraints imposed by maxMessageSize [RFC3412] and SNMP transport mappings.

syslogMsgFullCompliance.name: syslogMsgFullCompliance
syslogMsgFullCompliance.description: The compliance statement for implementations of the SYSLOG-MSG-MIB.

syslogMsgReadOnlyCompliance.name: syslogMsgReadOnlyCompliance
syslogMsgReadOnlyCompliance.description: The compliance statement for implementations of the SYSLOG-MSG-MIB that do not support read-write access.

syslogMsgNotificationCompliance.name: syslogMsgNotificationCompliance
syslogMsgNotificationCompliance.description: The compliance statement for implementations of the SYSLOG-MSG-MIB that do only generate notifications and do not provide a table to allow read access to SYSLOG message details.

syslogMsgNotificationGroup.name: syslogMsgNotificationGroup
syslogMsgNotificationGroup.description: The notifications emitted by this MIB module.

syslogMsgGroup.name: syslogMsgGroup
syslogMsgGroup.description: A collection of objects representing a SYSLOG message, excluding structured data elements.

syslogMsgSDGroup.name: syslogMsgSDGroup
syslogMsgSDGroup.description: A collection of objects representing the structured data elements of a SYSLOG message.

syslogMsgControlGroup.name: syslogMsgControlGroup
syslogMsgControlGroup.description: A collection of control objects to control the size of the syslogMsgTable and to enable/disable notifications.
